p=3D"headline">Mann-Whitney U-Test</h1>
</header><div class=3D"entry-content" itemprop=3D"text"><p>A Mann-Whitney <=
em>U</em>-test (also called the rank-sum test, or Wilcoxin-Mann-Whitney tes=
t) uses sample data to test if a <a href=3D"https://sites.utexas.edu/sos/va=
riables/" target=3D"_blank">numeric</a> outcome variable with <em>any </em>=
distribution differs across two independent groups. This test is an alterna=
tive to the <a href=3D"https://sites.utexas.edu/sos/guided/inferential/nume=
ric/onecat/2-groups/independent/two-sample-t/" target=3D"_blank">two-sample=
 independent <em>t</em>-test</a> when the data fails the <a href=3D"https:/=
/sites.utexas.edu/sos/normal/" target=3D"_blank">normality assumption</a> o=
r if the sample sizes in each group are too small to assess normality.</p>
<p>This test is run by ranking all observations and then finding the sum of=
 the ranks in each group. If the values in one group are generally higher t=
han in the other, the rank sums will differ. The test statistic, <em>U</em>=
 (or <em>W</em>), is a measure of the difference in rank sums.</p>
<p>Note: This test does not test specifically if the mean or median of two =
groups are equal, only if the overall distributions are significantly diffe=
rent or not.</p>
<p><strong>Assumptions:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href=3D"https://sites.utexas.edu/sos/random/">Random samples</a></li=
>
<li><a href=3D"https://sites.utexas.edu/sos/indobs/">Independent observatio=
ns</a></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Hypotheses:</strong></p>
<p><em>H</em><sub>o</sub>: The population distributions in the two groups a=
re the same.<br>
<em>H</em><sub>A</sub>: The population distributions in the two groups are =
<strong>not </strong>the same.</p>
<hr>
<p><strong>Example 1: Hand calculation video</strong></p>
<p>In this video, we=E2=80=99ll use a Mann-Whitney <em>U</em>-test to see i=
f the distribution of weights of female and male mosquitoes are significant=
ly different.</p>
<a id=3D"693a12fcc03a3" rel=3D"wp-video-lightbox" href=3D"https://www.youtu=
be.com/watch?v=3Da2Ng-cGgoIQ&amp;rel=3D0&amp;width=3D640&amp;height=3D480" =
title=3D""><div class=3D"wpvl_auto_thumb_box_wrapper"><div class=3D"wpvl_au=
to_thumb_box"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://img.youtube.com/vi/a2N=
g-cGgoIQ/0.jpg" class=3D"video_lightbox_auto_anchor_image" alt=3D"Mann Whit=
ney Hand Calc"><div class=3D"wpvl_auto_thumb_play"><img decoding=3D"async" =
src=3D"https://sites.utexas.edu/sos/wp-content/plugins/wp-video-lightbox/im=
ages/play.png" class=3D"wpvl_playbutton"></div></div></div></a>   =20
<p>Sample conclusion: This data suggests that there is no difference in the=
 weights of female and male mosquitoes (<em>U</em>=3D26, <em>p</em>&gt;0.05=
).</p>
<hr>
<p><strong>Example 2: How to run in RStudio</strong></p>
<p>This example tests if the number of days cats and dogs spend in the anim=
al shelter before being adopted is the same.</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://drive.google.com/uc?export=3Ddownload&amp;id=3D0B9b4o=
4b_Q7FcX2hyX3lseWZpUU0">Dataset used in video</a><br>
<a href=3D"https://drive.google.com/uc?export=3Ddownload&amp;id=3D0B9b4o4b_=
Q7FcUm85SHlUVDVZaTg">R script file used in video</a></p>
<a id=3D"693a12fcc0476" rel=3D"wp-video-lightbox" href=3D"https://www.youtu=
be.com/watch?v=3DcVhJmzJYHOo&amp;rel=3D0&amp;width=3D640&amp;height=3D480" =
title=3D""><div class=3D"wpvl_auto_thumb_box_wrapper"><div class=3D"wpvl_au=
to_thumb_box"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://img.youtube.com/vi/cVh=
JmzJYHOo/0.jpg" class=3D"video_lightbox_auto_anchor_image" alt=3D"Mann Whit=
ney R"><div class=3D"wpvl_auto_thumb_play"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"h=
ttps://sites.utexas.edu/sos/wp-content/plugins/wp-video-lightbox/images/pla=
y.png" class=3D"wpvl_playbutton"></div></div></div></a>   =20
<p>Sample conclusion: There is evidence to suggest that dogs and cats spend=
 different lengths of time in the shelter before getting adopted (<em>W</em=
>=3D45.5, <em>p</em>&lt;0.05).</p>
